rname is also common in Ulster.","Irish: variant of   McCutcheon   from <b>Mac Uisdein</b> or <b>Mac Uistein</b>.","History: In 1836 the newly founded city of Houston, TX, was named in honor of Sam Houston (1793–1863), soldier and statesman. As commander in chief of the Texan army he achieved Texas independence from Mexico by routing the army of the Mexican general Santa Anna. His ancestors were Ulster Scots who had emigrated to Philadelphia, PA, in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John de Houstoun II was born on 9 January 1355, in Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland, his father, Sir John de Houstoun, was 31 and his mother, Mary Colquhoun, was 31. He married Lady Mary Livingstone about 1369, in Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died on 9 January 1426, in Houston, Renfrewshire, Scotland, at the age of 71."},"et":{"9 January 1355–9 January 1426":"9. jaanuar 1355–9. jaanuar 1426","1355–1426":"1355–1426","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1372–Male":"1372–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1404–1450":"1404–1450","1376–1450":"1376–1450","1324–1400":"1324–1400","1324–1405":"1324–1405","9 January 1426":"9. jaanuar 1426","1450":"1450","1372":"1372","1350":"1350","Bef 1404":"enne 1404","1404":"1404","1426":"1426","1324":"1324","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","about 1369":"umbes 1369","1376":"1376","9 January 1355":"9. jaanuar 1355","1405":"1405","Rumanoch, Paisley, Renfrews